@MrSummitville dear sir. I was asking for the mile per hour  Because we get 15 - 45 mph wind from time to time... Except during thunderstorms. And they Can go from 30 -90 mph. I want to try My  hand at building a wind power device. But I was thinking I could regulate it at a Constance wind speed some how by gearing it. Didn't know for sure. Thought you might have some ideas.
     Thank you. Love your show. 
             Sincerely lee stewart

@ThinkingandTinkering It won't make any difference to the output, as you will have two half height rotors each taking half the amount of energy from the wind that the full size rotor does, so the output for a given wind speed will at best be the same - though additional frictional losses, coupled with additional dead space in the rotor assembly mean that the output would be reduced.
I do find it bizarre that someone who states that the strength of the magnets and the design of the coils aren't important thinks he can rival a commercially designed, tested and manufactured wind generator for efficiency.
As I noted in a comment on an earlier video in this series, there's no chance of such a jerry-built wind turbine/generator producing anything approaching a 1kW output...

@Ed R4 no, wind turbines gets the most of it's energy with the height and width of the blades, not the depth because it is too skiny. Boat sails does height, width and depth as well and it's much more eficient.
My question is if Betz Law and this formula presented here also works for sail boat like structures. Have you seen a Caravel? I'm sure it would not be pushed if they used blades instead of sails.
I mean, why not use wings in a circular form instead of blades?
